  "Problem Solving": {
    "definition": "The ability to define, analyze, and diagnose problems effectively to formulate strategic, data-informed solutions. Individuals strong in this area assess the full context of an issue, break complex challenges into manageable parts, and apply structured frameworks to guide their thinking. They remain objective, use both qualitative and quantitative inputs, and test hypotheses through experimentation or feedback loops. Strengthening this competency enables you to make informed decisions, even in uncertain situations, by identifying root causes, exploring innovative alternatives, and executing solution paths that are logical, measurable, and outcome driven.",
    "instruction": "Review the definition of Problem-Solving Competency and reflect on its relevance to your current responsibilities and future career aspirations. Based on the current demands of your role and the expectations of your future position, select one of the four effort levels, Critical, Important, Future Priority, or Personal Growth, that best reflects how urgently you need to develop this Competency. Document your choice, explain why this level best matches your situation, and list at least three development activities that you will begin implementing immediately to close the gap between today\u2019s performance and the standard required for your next career step.",
    "effortLevels": [
      {
        "level": "Critical (Must-Have Right Now)",
        "detail": "This Competency is absolutely necessary for your current role. You need to focus on developing it immediately to meet job expectations."
      },
      {
        "level": "Important (Good to Have Now)",
        "detail": "This Competency is helpful for your role and will make your work easier and more effective. It\u2019s worth working on, but it\u2019s not the top priority."
      },
      {
        "level": "Future Priority (Nice to Have Later)",
        "detail": "This Competency is not needed right now, but it will be important as your role grows or changes in the future. You can take your time to build it."
      },
      {
        "level": "Personal Growth (Optional)",
        "detail": "This Competency is not related to your current job but could be useful for personal or professional development in other areas. You can work on it when you want."
      }
    ],
    "behavioralIndicators": [
      "Defining, analyzing and diagnosing key components of a problem to formulate a solution.",
      "Clearly define the problem by identifying what is happening, who is affected, and why it matters. Set specific goals and anticipate potential obstacles to avoid jumping to conclusions.",
      "Utilize structured tools to identify root causes. Understand the scope, impact, and interrelated components to achieve a comprehensive diagnosis.",
      "Break down complex problems into smaller parts for focused analysis and examination. Allow space for abstract and creative thinking to explore innovative solutions.",
      "Use data to analyze objectively, combining quantitative and qualitative inputs. Avoid assumptions and consider team dynamics, culture, and external constraints.",
      "Evaluate the full context of the problem, identifying relationships and prioritizing what needs to be addressed first.",
      "Formulate and test hypotheses through pilots, experiments, or feedback loops to inform decision-making. Follow clear solution paths with logical planning.",
      "Generate multiple solutions and assess them using prioritization tools based on risk, impact, cost, and feasibility. Define success criteria clearly.",
      "Make sound decisions even with partial information by applying models like SWOT or risk analysis. Consider short- and long-term impact.",
      "Implement and monitor the solution, refining based on feedback and measuring outcomes against defined goals.",
      "Stay aware of cognitive biases, such as confirmation bias and overconfidence. Utilize structured thinking to remain objective and proactively prevent future issues."
    ],
    "developmentStrategies": [
      "Define the Problem with Precision: Practice structured problem definition daily by framing issues with the questions: What is happening? Who is affected? Why does it matter? and articulate these in writing to build clarity and discipline.",
      "Apply Root Cause Analysis Tools: Learn and apply diagnostic tools, such as the 5 Whys, Root Cause Tree, and Fishbone Diagram, to real-world problems at least twice a week to build muscle memory in cause identification.",
      "Break Down Problems Systematically: Train cognitive decomposition by routinely breaking down larger problems into sub-problems or systems (inputs, processes, outputs) and mapping relationships using mind maps or flowcharts.",
      "Develop Data Interpretation Skills: Develop data fluency by analyzing simple data sets and drawing insights using both descriptive stats and pattern recognition techniques; take action only after interpreting findings with a transparent logic chain.",
      "Map the Full Problem Context: Utilize context-mapping techniques to identify environmental, cultural, organizational, and interpersonal variables surrounding the problem, thereby understanding hidden constraints and dependencies.",
      "Experiment with Hypotheses in Action: Conduct hypothesis-based experiments for low-risk issues (e.g., A/B testing ideas with small groups), track outcomes, and reflect on what works and why; review outcomes every week.",
      "Evaluate Solution Options Strategically: Simulate solution trade-offs using decision matrices, cost-benefit grids, or impact-effort charts; make it a habit to generate at least three alternatives for every key decision.",
      "Strengthen Decision-Making Under Uncertainty: Study real-world decision cases where decisions were made with incomplete information; reverse-engineer the reasoning models used and apply similar structured judgment to own scenarios.",
      "Use Feedback to Improve Solutions: Incorporate feedback loops into every problem-solving effort, actively collect post-solution data and stakeholder inputs to evaluate effectiveness and adjust for continuous improvement.",
      "Control for Cognitive Biases: Build cognitive bias awareness by identifying one bias per week (e.g., confirmation bias, anchoring, sunk cost fallacy), journaling instances when it appeared, and practicing techniques to neutralize it."
    ],
    "reflectionQuestions": [
      "Which strategy helped you the most in starting tasks, and how did it change your approach?",
      "What task did you complete with confidence and initiative, and how did it feel afterward?",
      "What challenges did you face while implementing the strategies, and how did you overcome them?",
      "Any other observations or \u201cAHA\u201d moments that you want to capture for future reference?"
    ],
    "sourceFile": "TTIC19 - Problem Solving - Competency.docx"
  },
