  "Decision Making": {
    "definition": "The ability to evaluate all aspects of a situation and consistently make sound, timely, and accountable choices. Strong decision makers integrate data, stakeholder input, and consequence analysis to drive strategic outcomes, even under pressure or uncertainty. Developing this competency enhances your leadership effectiveness, increases trust and clarity within teams, and equips you to act decisively in complex, high-stakes environments. This plan offers a structured path to refine your judgment, increase your confidence in navigating ambiguity, and elevate the quality and impact of your decisions.",
    "instruction": "Review the definition of Decision-Making competency and reflect on its relevance to your current responsibilities and future career aspirations. Based on the current demands of your role and the expectations of your future position, select one of the four effort levels, Critical, Important, Future Priority, or Personal Growth, that best reflects how urgently you need to develop this Competency. Document your choice, explain why this level best matches your situation, and list at least three development activities that you will begin implementing immediately to close the gap between today\u2019s performance and the standard required for your next career step.",
    "effortLevels": [
      {
        "level": "Critical (Must-Have Right Now)",
        "detail": "This Competency is absolutely necessary for your current role. You need to focus on developing it immediately to meet job expectations."
      },
      {
        "level": "Important (Good to Have Now)",
        "detail": "This Competency is helpful for your role and will make your work easier and more effective. It\u2019s worth working on, but it\u2019s not the top priority."
      },
      {
        "level": "Future Priority (Nice to Have Later)",
        "detail": "This Competency is not needed right now, but it will be important as your role grows or changes in the future. You can take your time to build it."
      },
      {
        "level": "Personal Growth (Optional)",
        "detail": "This Competency is not related to your current job but could be useful for personal or professional development in other areas. You can work on it when you want."
      }
    ],
    "behavioralIndicators": [
      "Analyzing all aspects of a situation to make consistently sound and timely decisions.",
      "Analyzes all dimensions of a situation, including risks, stakeholders, timing, historical components, and potential trade-offs, before initiating a decision, ensuring no critical detail is overlooked.",
      "Gathers input from relevant sources (data, team insights, subject-matter experts) and asks the right questions, rather than relying on assumptions, to build a strong, evidence-backed rationale for action.",
      "Anticipates both immediate and downstream consequences of a decision by mentally simulating potential outcomes across multiple scenarios.",
      "Makes complex or high-stakes decisions within defined time constraints, even when information is incomplete or when uncertainty is high.",
      "Pushes forward with decisions despite external resistance, emotional pressure, or disagreement when the data and rationale support the choice.",
      "Demonstrates a straightforward, structured thought process and can explain the \u2018why\u2019 behind each decision with logical consistency and strategic alignment.",
      "Accepts full accountability for the results of decisions, whether successful or not, and addresses the fallout without shifting blame.",
      "Uses feedback and outcome analysis to refine future decision-making, learning from both successes and failures to improve judgment over time.",
      "Balances decisiveness with flexibility, knowing when to stick to a choice and when to pivot based on new evidence or shifting contexts.",
      "Maintains emotional control and clarity of thought in high-pressure moments, ensuring that decisions are based on logic and principle rather than reaction or bias."
    ],
    "developmentStrategies": [
      "Practice Structured Decision Frameworks (e.g., SWOT, Cost-Benefit, 5 Whys): Use analytical tools consistently to evaluate all angles, facts, assumptions, risks, and trade-offs before committing to a choice.",
      "Run \u2018Pre-Mortem\u2019 Scenarios for Every Major Decision: Before finalizing a decision, imagine that it failed, then identify what could have caused the failure. This enhances foresight and consequence anticipation.",
      "Regularly Use Decision Logs or journals to document the rationale, alternatives considered and expected outcomes of significant decisions. Review past entries periodically to refine judgment.",
      "Engage in Cross-Functional Simulations and Role-Plays: Participate in time-bound decision-making exercises that simulate real-world complexity and opposition. This strengthens decisiveness under pressure.",
      "Solicit Diverse Inputs Before Making a Decision, Then Make an Independent Choice: Train yourself to collect varied perspectives (from the team, data, and experts), then synthesize that input into a single, informed decision.",
      "Learn to Tolerate Ambiguity and Incomplete Information: Deliberately practice decision-making in gray areas, using intuition backed by structured logic, especially when the \u201cperfect\u201d answer isn\u2019t available.",
      "Build Accountability Contracts for Your Decisions: Create a habit of clearly stating your choice and publicly owning the outcome, reinforcing ownership even when the decision is difficult or risky.",
      "Analyze Your Past Decisions with 20/20 Hindsight: Break down both successful and failed decisions to understand the thinking process, emotional state, and external pressures involved. Identify your patterns.",
      "Train Emotional Regulation Techniques: Use breathing, visualization, or cognitive reframing to maintain clarity during high-stakes, high-pressure decisions. Emotional control directly affects decision quality.",
      "Adopt a \u201cDecide-Then-Refine\u201d Mindset: Emphasize making well-reasoned decisions quickly, then iterating or correcting course based on feedback and results, rather than waiting for perfect certainty."
    ],
    "reflectionQuestions": [
      "Which strategy helped you the most in starting tasks, and how did it change your approach?",
      "What task did you complete with confidence and initiative, and how did it feel afterward?",
      "What challenges did you face while implementing the strategies, and how did you overcome them?",
      "Any other observations or \u201cAHA\u201d moments that you want to capture for future reference?"
    ],
    "sourceFile": "TTIC7 - Decision Making - Competency.docx"
  },
